article.headline: San Diego State 86, California 79
article.story: SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Steve Fisher's San Diego State Aztecs couldn't have asked for much more on Saturday, when they got a rare win over a Pac-10 team and a big performance by a newcomer who'd been serving a suspension. Jerome Habel scored 23 points in his SDSU debut and the Aztecs continued their best start in 22 seasons by beating California 86-79. The Aztecs are 5-0 for the first time since winning their first eight games in 1984-85. "Cal's a big-time program with a big-time team and we feel we're a big-time program with a big-time team," said SDSU guard Brandon Heath, who led the Aztecs into the NCAA tournament last year. "These are the types of games we have to win." Mohamed Abukar added 22 points and Heath 19 for the Aztecs, who beat a Pac-10 team for the first time in eight games. Their last win over a Pac-10 team came against Arizona State on Dec. 16, 2000. The Golden Bears had beaten SDSU each of the last two seasons, including 82-64 at Berkeley last season. Habel, a junior college transfer, was suspended on Oct. 31 for violating unspecified team rules. "It was a new experience. It felt like home," Habel said. "Jerome brought a lot of energy," Heath said. "We knew all along he could play big. And others got to see that tonight." Fisher was happy, too. "Habel had a tremendous night," the coach said. "He gives us a great option that complements our team." Ryan Anderson scored 21 points for the Golden Bears (1-1) before fouling out with 5:13 left. SDSU's biggest lead was 63-52 with 8:33 left after Richie Williams' coast-to-coast layup capped an 8-0 run. Cal quickly got it back into single digits, but Habel helped keep the Aztecs ahead by scoring nine points in the last seven minutes. Cal coach Ben Braun was disappointed in his defense, which got beat in transition. "Every time they sensed some miscommunication, they sensed tentativeness on our part, and they really made us pay," Braun said. Cal's Jerome Randle made two free throws with 27.2 seconds left to make it 80-77. Abukar saved the ball from going out of bounds and flipped it to Habel, whose dunk gave SDSU an 82-77 lead with 17 seconds left. Randle made a layup with 13 seconds left before SDSU closed it out with two free throws apiece by Abukar and Kyle Spain. Randle scored 18 points, Omar Wilkes 15 and DeVon Hardin 10. The Aztecs took a 7-0 lead and led by seven points two other times in the first half. Cal led 31-30 at halftime.
